1 employee possessed as a judge or employee before [the effective date of this act], including:
2 (i) rights to tenure in office and of pay;
3 (ii) rights to vacation pay, sick pay, and leave;
4 (iii) rights under any retirement or personnel plan or labor union contract;
5 (iv) rights to compensatory time earned; and
6 (v) any other rights under any law or administrative policy.
7 (b) This section is not intended to create any new rights for the workers' compensation judge or
8 any employee but to continue only those rights in effect before [the effective date of this act].
9 (2) The supreme court succeeds to the rights to all real and personal property of that agency
10 relating to the functions or parts of the office of workers' compensation judge. The property includes real
11 property, records, office equipment, supplies, contracts, books, papers, documents, maps, appropriations,
12 accounts within and outside of the state treasury, funds, vehicles, and all other similar property. However, the
13 supreme court may not use or divert money in a fund or account for a purpose other than provided by law. The
14 governor shall resolve any conflict as to the proper disposition of the property, and the governor's decision is
15 final.
16 (3) The supreme court succeeds to the rules and orders of the office of workers' compensation
17 judge relating to the functions or parts of functions transferred in [this act]. The rules and orders of the office of
18 workers' compensation judge in effect before [the effective date of this act] remain in effect until amended,
19 repealed, superseded, or nullified by proper authority or by law.
